# End-to-End Verifier (single-shot e2e/integration verifier for one PR)
#
# Triggers, response surfaces, and setup preconditions are defined in
# the structured `spec:` block below. The verdict comment is always
# POSTed fresh, never PATCHed in place — see the verdict-comment skill.
#
# # When to use this template
#
# Use it when:
# - You want to automatically verify PRs against a deployed system (API,
#   web service, CLI, mobile, etc.) and post results on GitHub.
# - You have a safe test environment where the verifier can deploy
#   changes if needed (personal dev namespace, staging, sandbox, etc.).
#
# # Before adopting this template
#
# Fill in the required setup preconditions (discovered during Advisor
# onboarding or by direct team knowledge):
#
# 1. **Surfaces to verify** (UI/browser, API, CLI, logs, mobile, etc.)
# 2. **Toolchain** the verifier needs on PATH in the environment image
#    (language runtimes, browsers, CLIs your project's test suites depend on)
# 3. **Secrets** wired into Secrets Manager for each surface (names only,
#    never commit values) — e.g. TEST_USER_LOGIN, API_KEY_STAGING
# 4. **Safe deploy target** where the verifier may deploy test changes
#    when the proof path requires it (personal dev namespace, staging
#    preview URL, ephemeral environment, sandbox tenant). Never production
#    or shared environments.
#
# Document these in the verifier's playbook file:
# `org/experts/verification/playbook/{owner}/{repo}.md`. See knowledgebase
# `skills/verification/vfs-and-playbooks.md` for the file format
# (`## Setup` / `## Exercise` / `## Teardown` / `## Notes`).
#
# The system prompt body lives at knowledgebase
# `expert-templates/prompts/end-to-end-verifier.md` and is pulled in via
# `<include>`. Core verifier skills (`e2e-scope`, `vfs-and-playbooks`,
# `secret-redaction`, `plan-selection`, `verdict-comment`,
# `cosmos-hosted-artifacts`) and the
# verifier-specific memory bindings (`verification-load-memory`,
# `verification-feedback-capture`) ship as committed knowledgebase files
# under `skills/verification/` and are resolved from this repo at
# session start — adopters do not need to seed tenant VFS for the bundle
# to apply. End-of-run curation and pruning use the generic memory skills
# (knowledgebase `skills/memory/curate-knowledge.md` and
# `skills/memory/prune-and-compact.md`) directly, bound to
# `TEAM=verification` and `SCOPE={owner}/{repo}` via the verifier
# prompt's context block. The verifier owns three tenant-scope files per
# repo: a human-edited playbook at
# `org/experts/verification/playbook/{owner}/{repo}.md` (verifier
# read-only — never written), an append-only breadcrumb file at
# `org/experts/verification/breadcrumbs/{owner}/{repo}.md`, and an
# auto-curated knowledge file at
# `org/experts/verification/knowledge/{owner}/{repo}.md` (whole-file
# rewrite from breadcrumbs by the generic curate-knowledge skill, pruned
# in place by prune-and-compact). The verifier itself tolerates a
# missing playbook at runtime (plan selection falls through to the
# next priority — PR body, memory, broader-ask, bounded investigation),
# but Advisor-mediated wiring seeds the playbook before enabling the
# trigger; see step 5 in "Before applying" below.
#
# # Before applying
#
# Verifier sessions consume the configured environment image and the
# Secrets Manager state at boot — they do not install tooling or mint
# credentials at session start. Walk the operator through the steps
# below before `apply`. These are recommendations, not hard gates;
# when something is unknown, prefer to pause and ask.
#
# 1. **Discover the customer's stack before asking anything else.**
#    Do not assume any cloud, orchestrator, build system, language,
#    or testing tool — most customers are not on GCP, many do not
#    use Kubernetes, and the rest of the stack varies just as
#    widely. Lead with open questions and let the answers shape
#    every later question. Useful prompts:
#      - *"Which verification surfaces should this expert cover —
#        UI/browser, HTTP/RPC API, CLI/TUI, logs from the running
#        system, a deployed target, mobile/desktop, async/webhook,
#        something else?"*
#      - *"What is the project's primary language and toolchain,
#        and which build / test / package commands do humans
#        actually run to exercise the change?"*
#      - *"Where does the code run when you test it end-to-end — a
#        local process, a container, a hosted cloud (which one?),
#        an on-prem cluster, a managed PaaS, a device, none of the
#        above?"*
#      - *"Which CLI tools, SDKs, browsers, or services does that
#        path need? Anything in-house or unusual?"*
#    Record the operator's answers — they drive steps 2 and 3.
#
# 2. **Confirm the environment image has the tooling the customer
#    actually named.** The verifier runs whatever is on `PATH` in
#    the configured `<ENVIRONMENT_ID>`; it does not install tooling
#    at session start. For each item the operator listed in step 1,
#    confirm the corresponding binary, SDK, or browser is present
#    in the image. Do not check for tools the operator did not
#    name. If anything required is missing, rebuild the environment
#    with a provision script per `guides/cloud/environments.md`
#    before applying.
#
# 3. **Confirm auth and secrets are wired into Secrets Manager for
#    the surfaces from step 1, using the operator's vocabulary.**
#    User/tenant secrets are managed on the webapp `/secrets` page
#    (or via `auggie cloud secret`) and auto-inject into the VM as
#    env vars or file mounts per `guides/secrets-and-access.md`.
#    Walk through the surfaces the operator named, one at a time;
#    skip the rest. Sample shapes — substitute the operator's
#    actual stack throughout, do not paste these verbatim:
#      - *"For the {UI / API / CLI / …} surface, what credentials
#        does an end-to-end run need (test account login, API key,
#        bearer token, mTLS cert, signed cookie, …)? Are those
#        already in Secrets Manager, and under what names?"*
#      - *"If the surface runs against a hosted environment (cloud,
#        cluster, PaaS, device farm, …), which one, and what
#        credential shape does it use ({cloud}-issued key, IAM
#        role, service principal, kubeconfig file, SSH key,
#        device-farm token, …)? Is that credential mounted as an
#        env var or as a file secret (`augment:mount_point` tag),
#        and which context / project / account name should the
#        verifier use?"*
#      - *"If the surface reads logs or metrics, from which
#        provider ({operator's actual observability stack}), and is
#        the matching read-only credential already in Secrets
#        Manager?"*
#      - *"When the proof path requires a deploy, which target is
#        safe to deploy into — a per-user namespace, preview URL,
#        ephemeral environment, sandbox tenant, …?"* The prompt
#        declines deploys without a named safe target and never
#        touches production, staging, shared, or another user's
#        environment.
#    If the operator isn't sure for any of these, treat the
#    corresponding surface as out of scope for now or pause and
#    follow up. Never paste secret values into this bundle, the
#    prompt body, PR or Slack posts, VFS, or memory — the
#    prompt's secret-redaction and cleanup-side-effects skills are
#    binding (already wired into the prompt body via `<include>`).
#
# 4. **Fill in the placeholders below.**
#
# | Placeholder        | Where                                          |
# |--------------------|------------------------------------------------|
# | `<ENVIRONMENT_ID>` | `spec.expert.environment.id`                   |
# | `<OWNER/REPO>`     | GitHub `pull_request` and `issue_comment`      |
# |                    | trigger filters — replace with the exact repo  |
# |                    | full name (for example `acme/web-app`).        |
# | `<CHANNEL_ID>`     | Slack trigger filter — delete the trigger if   |
# |                    | the bot should not listen on a Slack channel.  |
#
# 5. **Seed the verifier's playbook for each repo in the trigger
#    filter** before enabling the `pull_request` trigger. The
#    playbook write is a hard precondition: do not enable the
#    trigger and do not declare verifier setup complete until
#    `org/experts/verification/playbook/{owner}/{repo}.md` exists
#    for every `{owner}/{repo}` named in the trigger's
#    `repository.full_name` filter (one file per repo; if the `in`
#    list carries multiple repos, run this loop once per repo). If
#    the operator declines to seed, leave the trigger disabled and
#    surface that explicitly — never silently skip.
#
#    The questionnaire IS the playbook draft — write each section
#    as the answer comes in, do not collect answers in prose and
#    translate later. Walk the operator through the four reserved
#    sections in order, in their vocabulary (no Cosmos jargon),
#    reusing the discovery prompts from steps 1–3 above for
#    question content:
#      - `## Setup` — what brings the code under test up (deploy
#        command, build, environment image expectations, secret
#        names already wired, dev-target name). Required.
#      - `## Exercise` — the e2e/integration commands or surface
#        invocations that prove the change. Required.
#      - `## Teardown` — cleanup steps if any. Optional; write the
#        heading with `(none)` if there's nothing.
#      - `## Notes` — gotchas, discriminators, infra quirks every
#        run should preload. Optional; write `(none)` if empty.
#
#    Always emit every `##` heading even when an optional section
#    is empty. These four titles are reserved for this playbook
#    file and must not be reused by other verifier-owned files
#    (the auto-curated knowledge file uses different titles such
#    as `## Setup notes`, `## Known flakes`, or path-glob
#    headings). Per-surface sub-sections one level deeper
#    (`### api`, `### web`, …) are allowed inside `## Setup` /
#    `## Exercise` when the repo has distinct surfaces — at
#    runtime the verifier picks scopes whose declared path
#    prefixes match the PR's changed files.
#
#    After the four sections have content, summarize the
#    assembled Markdown back to the operator in one block and ask
#    via `ask-user` for an explicit go before writing. Three
#    options: "Write it" (proceed), "Let me edit first" (accept
#    the edited Markdown verbatim and write that), "Don't seed
#    yet — leave the trigger disabled" (abort and surface the
#    disabled state).
#
#    On go, create the parent directory and write to
#    `org/experts/verification/playbook/{owner}/{repo}.md`. The
#    verifier itself never writes to this file — it loads it
#    read-only on every run. Future updates flow through the
#    operator (or another Advisor session), never through the
#    verifier.
#
#    Self-check (required before enabling the trigger): read the
#    file back and report one line per repo to the operator. Use
#    `✓` only if the section has substantive content; use
#    `(empty)` for optional sections the operator left blank.
#    Example output for two repos — first had all four sections
#    filled, second left the optional sections blank:
#
#        Seeded playbook: org/experts/verification/playbook/acme/api.md — ✓ Setup, ✓ Exercise, ✓ Teardown, ✓ Notes
#        Seeded playbook: org/experts/verification/playbook/acme/web.md — ✓ Setup, ✓ Exercise, (empty) Teardown, (empty) Notes
#
#    If `## Setup` or `## Exercise` is `(empty)`, the precondition
#    is not met — do not enable the trigger and re-enter the
#    questionnaire for that repo.
#
#    See knowledgebase `skills/verification/vfs-and-playbooks.md`
#    for the broader file-ownership contract across the
#    verifier's three per-repo memory files (playbook,
#    breadcrumbs, knowledge).

apiVersion: poseidon.augmentcode.com/v1alpha1
kind: ExpertBundle
metadata:
  name: end-to-end-verifier
spec:
  expert:
    displayName: End-to-End Verifier
    description: Exercises the feature in your PR and posts results (and screenshots) to GitHub.
    visibility: tenant
    systemPrompt: |-
      <include src="kb://expert-templates/prompts/end-to-end-verifier.md" />
    model: claude-opus-4-8 # If Opus 4.8 is unavailable, use GPT 5.5 (gpt-5-5).
    includeDefaultSystemPrompt: true
    capabilities:
      - WEB_ACCESS
      - GITHUB_APP
      - SLACK
    environment:
      id: <ENVIRONMENT_ID>
      resources:
        cpuCores: 4
        memoryMib: 8192
    initialMessages: []
    userInstructions: |-
      Paste a GitHub PR URL into the chat box to verify a PR on demand.
      The expert also runs automatically when a fresh PR is opened or
      marked ready for review, when a PR comment starts with `cosmos
      verify`, or when the Augment bot is @-mentioned in the configured
      Slack channel with a GitHub PR URL.

      Each session verifies one PR end-to-end (checkout → setup → exercise
      → proof bundle), posts a fresh verdict comment back on the PR, and
      terminates.

      **Setup preconditions** — see the onboarding header in this bundle
      file for setup preconditions (surfaces, toolchain, secrets, deploy
      target), or run the Advisor for interactive walkthrough.
    placeholderText: GitHub PR URL
    workerExpertIds: []
    useAllExpertsAsWorkers: false
  triggers:
    # GitHub trigger: a fresh pull request that is ready for human review —
    # either opened directly as a non-draft PR or moved out of draft via
    # `ready_for_review`. Mirrors the canonical "PR created" filter used by
    # other tenant-visibility GitHub experts (see pr-risk-analyzer).
    - name: pr-created
      type: github
      eventType: pull_request
      filter: '{"and": [{"in": [{"var": "repository.full_name"}, ["<OWNER/REPO>"]]}, {"or": [{"==": [{"var": "action"}, "ready_for_review"]}, {"and": [{"==": [{"var": "action"}, "opened"]}, {"==": [{"var": "pull_request.draft"}, false]}]}]}]}'
    # GitHub trigger: any new PR comment whose body contains the
    # `cosmos verify` invocation. The verifier skill set treats the comment
    # author as the requester and the PR as `pr_url`.
    - name: pr-comment-cosmos-verify
      type: github
      eventType: issue_comment
      filter: |-
        {"and": [
          {"in": [{"var": "repository.full_name"}, ["<OWNER/REPO>"]]},
          {"==": [{"var": "action"}, "created"]},
          {"!!": [{"var": "issue.pull_request"}]},
          {"in": ["cosmos verify", {"var": "comment.body"}]}
        ]}
    # Slack trigger: an @-mention of the Augment bot in the configured
    # channel. The verifier extracts the first GitHub PR URL from the
    # message text or surrounding thread; if none is present it asks once
    # on the originating thread and stops. Delete this trigger if GitHub
    # is the only entry point for your team.
    - name: slack-app-mention
      type: slack
      eventType: app_mention
      filter: |-
        {"and": [
          {"==": [{"var": "event.channel"}, "<CHANNEL_ID>"]},
          {"==": [{"var": "event.type"}, "app_mention"]}
        ]}
